File: lichen/subsys/lichen/meshtastic/adapter.c:1051-1065

  static void sort_peers_by_eui64(struct nodedb_peer_state *state)
  {
      for (size_t i = 1U; i < state->peer_count; i++) {
          struct lichen_meshtastic_peer_snapshot peer = state->peers[i];
          size_t j = i;
          while (j > 0U &&
                 memcmp(state->peers[j - 1U].eui64, peer.eui64, sizeof(peer.eui64)) > 0) {
              state->peers[j] = state->peers[j - 1U];
              j--;
          }
          state->peers[j] = peer;
      }
  }

This is O(n^2) insertion sort. With MESHTASTIC_NODEDB_MAX_PEERS potentially being a configurable value, large peer counts could cause performance issues.

For embedded systems with small peer counts (e.g., <50), this is acceptable. But if peer_count could reach hundreds, consider qsort() or other O(n log n) algorithm.

Also, each swap copies the full lichen_meshtastic_peer_snapshot struct (56+ bytes). Consider sorting indices instead.
